<TITLE> Former Observer editor dies at 96 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 13 (bdnews24.com)  Prominent journalist Obaidul Huq died from old-age complications Saturday at the age of 96. A namaz-e-janaza was held for the former editor of The Bangladesh Observer at Banani Mosque Saturday evening, his family said. President Iajuddin Ahmed, chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed and information adviser Mainul Hosein expressed deep sorrows at the death of the veteran journalist. Huq left behind four sons and one daughter. His son Mashukul Huq works for the magazine of The Bangladesh Observer, the once-top selling English language newspaper. Huq was the author of a number of books and anthologies. He was the chairman of the trust that ran The Bangladesh Times and Dainik Bangla. Huq was a pioneer in Bangla motion-picture making in the South Asian region. Huq won several awards, including Ekushey Award, for his excellence in journalism. bdnews
